  <h1>How Sexual Harassment Settlements Are Calculated</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Workplace sexual harassment settlements are not arbitrary &mdash; they are negotiated against a damages structure set by
    Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the Civil Rights Act of 1991, and parallel state statutes. Once you understand
    the components, the employer-size caps, and the mitigation rules, you can read a settlement offer and tell whether it sits at,
    above, or below the rational range for the case. This guide walks through each part.
  </p>

  <h2>The four damages components</h2>

  <h3>Back pay</h3>
  <p>
    Back pay covers wages, bonuses, commissions, and the dollar value of lost benefits from the adverse employment action through
    the date of judgment or settlement. It is equitable relief under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-5(g) and sits <em>outside</em> the
    &sect; 1981a(b)(3) damages cap, which makes it the workhorse of high-tenure terminated-plaintiff cases. Two adjustments matter:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mitigation.</strong> The plaintiff has a duty to make reasonable efforts to find comparable work. Interim earnings offset back pay dollar-for-dollar. Failure to search reduces or eliminates back pay (<em>Ford Motor Co. v. EEOC</em>, 458 U.S. 219 (1982)).</li>
    <li><strong>Prejudgment interest.</strong> Available in the court&rsquo;s discretion, calculated at the federal rate or the state-law equivalent. Often a meaningful add-on in older cases.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Front pay</h3>
  <p>
    Future earnings the plaintiff would have received but for the unlawful conduct, in lieu of reinstatement. Front pay is
    equitable, not capped, and not always awarded. The Supreme Court confirmed in <em>Pollard v. E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co.</em>,
    532 U.S. 843 (2001), that front pay sits outside the &sect; 1981a(b)(3) cap. Courts weigh:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Plaintiff&rsquo;s age and remaining work life.</li>
    <li>Earnings differential at the new job, if any.</li>
    <li>Reasonable likelihood of obtaining comparable employment.</li>
    <li>The toxicity of the workplace (a strong factor against reinstatement, in favor of front pay).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Compensatory damages</h3>
  <p>
    Non-pecuniary harm: emotional distress, mental anguish, loss of enjoyment of life, inconvenience, loss of professional
    reputation, plus out-of-pocket medical and therapy costs. The Civil Rights Act of 1991 added these to Title VII at
    &sect; 1981a(a)(1). Compensatory damages are subject to the employer-size cap when combined with punitive damages.
    Documentary support &mdash; a therapist&rsquo;s notes, a treating physician&rsquo;s diagnosis of PTSD or anxiety, medication
    records &mdash; substantially affects the compensatory number.
  </p>

  <h3>Punitive damages</h3>
  <p>
    Available against private employers (not federal, state, or local governments) on proof of <em>malice</em> or
    <em>reckless indifference</em> to the plaintiff&rsquo;s federally protected rights (<em>Kolstad v. American Dental Ass&rsquo;n</em>,
    527 U.S. 526 (1999)). The standard is the employer&rsquo;s state of mind, not the egregiousness of the conduct alone. An
    employer can sometimes defeat punitives by showing good-faith efforts to comply with Title VII through a published and
    enforced anti-harassment policy.
  </p>

  <h2>The 42 U.S.C. &sect; 1981a(b)(3) employer-size cap</h2>
  <p>
    Combined compensatory plus punitive damages under Title VII are capped per plaintiff by the employer&rsquo;s number of US
    employees in each of 20 or more calendar weeks of the current or preceding calendar year:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>15&ndash;100 employees:</strong> $50,000.</li>
    <li><strong>101&ndash;200 employees:</strong> $100,000.</li>
    <li><strong>201&ndash;500 employees:</strong> $200,000.</li>
    <li><strong>501+ employees:</strong> $300,000.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The cap has not been adjusted for inflation since 1991. In 2026 dollars the $300,000 cap is worth roughly half of what it was
    when enacted. This is the single most consequential limitation in federal employment-discrimination law and is the reason
    sophisticated plaintiff&rsquo;s lawyers nearly always plead a state-law theory alongside Title VII where the state law is more generous.
  </p>

  <h2>State-law overlays that change the math</h2>
  <p>
    Several state statutes either remove the damages cap entirely, lower the employee-count threshold for coverage, or both.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>California FEHA</strong> (Gov. Code &sect; 12940 et seq.) &mdash; no cap; covers employers with 5+ employees (1+ for harassment); 3-year filing window with the Civil Rights Department.</li>
    <li><strong>New York Human Rights Law</strong> (Exec. Law &sect; 296) &mdash; no cap as amended in 2019; covers all employers regardless of size for harassment; 3-year limitations period for sexual harassment claims.</li>
    <li><strong>New Jersey LAD</strong> (N.J.S.A. 10:5-1 et seq.) &mdash; no cap; broad compensatory and punitive availability.</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois Human Rights Act</strong> (775 ILCS 5/1-101 et seq.) &mdash; no cap as amended; covers all employers.</li>
    <li><strong>Massachusetts G.L. c. 151B</strong> &mdash; no cap; treble back-pay availability in retaliation cases.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The settlement number for the same set of facts can differ by a factor of three or more depending on whether a state-law
    overlay is available. This is why &ldquo;state&rdquo; is a meaningful input on the calculator.
  </p>

  <h2>Fee-shifting under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-5(k)</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII authorizes the court, in its discretion, to award reasonable attorney fees to a prevailing party. A prevailing
    plaintiff is almost always entitled to fees; a prevailing employer rarely is (only on a showing the claim was frivolous,
    unreasonable, or without foundation). In settlement, the employer effectively pays the plaintiff&rsquo;s reasonable fees on
    top of the damages. In small-cap-employer cases, fee-shifting often exceeds the damages award.
  </p>
  <p>
    State statutes have similar fee-shifting provisions, generally on the same lodestar (hours times rate, with multipliers
    available) framework.
  </p>

  <h2>Worked example: hostile environment, 250-employee employer, Texas, no termination</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Severity: severe (repeated, supervisor) &rarr; compensatory midpoint approximately $175,000.</li>
    <li>No tangible adverse action &rarr; back pay near $0.</li>
    <li>Employer 201&ndash;500 &rarr; $200,000 federal cap on combined comp + punitive.</li>
    <li>Texas: no state-law overlay that uncaps.</li>
    <li>Attorney fees recoverable separately, frequently $100,000&ndash;$300,000 by the time a case settles after charge and investigation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Realistic settlement range $95,000&ndash;$280,000 on the damages side, plus fees. The cap drives the high end.
  </p>

  <h2>Worked example: quid pro quo, constructive discharge, 2,000-employee employer, California, $140,000 salary, 4-year tenure</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Severity: egregious &rarr; compensatory midpoint approximately $400,000.</li>
    <li>Quid pro quo with tangible action &rarr; vicarious liability, no <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> defense.</li>
    <li>Constructive discharge &rarr; back pay approximately one year salary minus mitigation, plus modest front pay (e.g., $100,000 net).</li>
    <li>California FEHA &rarr; no damages cap.</li>
    <li>Attorney fees recoverable.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Realistic settlement range $400,000&ndash;$1,200,000 on the damages side, with documentary evidence pulling toward the high end.
    Fee-shifted attorney fees often match the damages award.
  </p>

  <h2>What the calculator deliberately does not model</h2>
  <p>
    Trial-risk premium, opposing-counsel reputation, prior settlements within the same company, the employer&rsquo;s insurance
    carrier&rsquo;s appetite for trial, the plaintiff&rsquo;s credibility on the stand, and the location-specific jury attitudes
    that materially affect settlement value. Those move cases in mediation; none are knowable from a web form. Use the calculator
    to get the order of magnitude right, then talk to a lawyer.
  </p>
